You can get close to what you want by taking multiple generic arguments at the interface level and none at the function level.

    interface A&lt;T, S extends V&lt;T&gt;&gt; {
        public T f(S v);
    }

    class B&lt;T&gt; extends A&lt;T, V1&lt;T&gt;&gt; {

        @Override // Here it gives error: Method does not override method from its superclass
        public T f(V1&lt;T&gt; v) {
            return v.v1();
        }
    }

Note that this isn&#39;t *quite* the guarantee you were looking for, as someone could come along and write some `class C extends A&lt;Integer, V1&lt;Integer&gt;&gt;` that only works for integers and no other type. But to do that, you&#39;d need something called [higher-kinded polymorphism](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/876948/higher-kinded-generics-in-java) which is not supported in Java.

